	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=4&mid=97190793921642>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=97190793921642>RE: What can I do to survive in groups as a bard?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=97190793921642#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Oct 18th 6:25 PM 2000</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=2116><span id= >Amadeos</span></a><br><span id=notbold>2 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>One of the biggest ways of getting multiple mobs Not to aggro on you is this:&nbsp;&nbsp;When the puller says 'incoming', stop playing heal or manasong, or whatever your playing in the downtime.  Give the mobs a few seconds to focus on someone else, then start playing your songs.  This should work in the beginning but if the other mobs are not being attacked then eventually they will start hitting you depending on what your playing...  If there is no enchanter in the group and you do not feel comfortable doing crowd control yourself, instruct the tank to make sure to attack/taunt all the mobs a few times so they stay aggroed on him, besides thats the tanks job - to take damage not just deliver...  If you have a competent healer that wont be a problem...<br><br></p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
